                  <note resp="corr.">Mss. Esad Ef, 1413. 1a-47a (not 37). An excellent vowelled copy, written by a disiple of SQ’s, Qasam [b.] MuΩaffar [b. ¡Asåkir], and probably copied from SQ’s copy. No date, but it must be pre-673/1274. (JC/SH) Shehit Ali 1340. 110a-150a is in fact an extract from Tadiråt al-ilåhiya (RG 716). Only 150a-153a is an extract from ¡Anqa⁄. This whole collection is dated 789H and was written by Abd al-Kar∆m b. Ab¬ Bakr al-Jabarti, who was the teacher of ¡Abd al-Karim al-J∆l∆. (JC/SH). Carullah 986 , 51b-60. Like GE (see Islamic Sainthood…, pp.199-200) we could find nothing which supports OY’s claim that it was copied by a disciple in the lifetime of IA. But GE ‘s assessment is that this is nevertheless an important copy, probably taken from the original. (JC/SH).</note>
                  <note resp="additions_0">Mss. Berlin 3266 (probably the oldest surviving ms. of a work by Ibn ‘Arab∆). Commentary on the Dibâja by Hasan b. Muhammad al- Hanafî al- Halabî, ms. BN. 2669, ff. 156-166. Publications Cairo editions, 1373H (1954), 1997 and 1998. A commentary by M. Ibrah∆m M. Sålim, Kashf al-Gha†å⁄ ¡an Asrår al-¡Anqå¡, Cairo, 1999. Translations Into English by G. Elmore as Islamic Sainthood in the Fullness of Time, Leiden, 1998. (MC)</note>
