                     notAfter="1111"
                     cert="low"
                     calendar="Hijri-qamari"
                     evidence="conjecture">Terminus post quem and terminus ante quem</date>
               <note type="dateNote">Note on Date of Composition</note>
               <placeName type="fmPlace"/>
               <note type="placeNote">Note on Place of Composition</note>
               <note type="compositionNote"/>
               <!-- Contents -->
               <noteGrp type="workDesc">
                  <note type="description">The function, states and places of the saints who have the spiritual rank of the ‘pole’ (quṭb). This is a series of chapters on the aqṭāb which became part of the FM chapters 462-489, with poems up to 557 (corresponding to sifr 17 of 20 in the first recension).</note>
                  <note type="structure">Structure of Work</note>
                  <note type="contentsNote">Note on Contents</note>
               </noteGrp>
               <!-- Stemmatics -->
               <note type="stemmatics">OY lists only one ms, Koprulu 766, 1-146, which is an early text. It carries no date, but evidence suggests that it may date to late 7th century (the scribe is the same as that of Farghānī’s Muntahā al-madārik listed here http://41.32.191.214/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=39750, dated 704H). We have found a second text in the Ulu Cami library in Bursa, but as we have not yet obtained a digital copy, cannot compare the two mss. JC notes discrepancy between the text and the added red numbers from ch. 4 onwards: from chapter “five” to chapter “sixteen” the red ink number (467-478) is one less than the corresponding FM chapter number (ch.468-479); from chapter “seventeen” to “sixty” the red ink number (479-522) is four less than the corresponding FM chapter number (ch.483-526); from chapter “sixty-one” to “ninety-one” (the last in the ms) there are no red ink numbers – and these correspond to FM ch.527-557. In summary, the text of RG 35 K. al-Aqṭāb has the appearance of a highly abbreviated version of FM ch.462-557, omitting ch.480-482 entirely. It is possible that RG 35 is an early form or summary of sifr 17 of the first recension text of FM.</note>
