               <explicit type="muqadimma" xml:lang="ara">Closing Words of Text (Arabic script)</explicit>
               <note type="textualIdentifiersNote">Note on Textual Identifiers</note>
               <!-- Authorship and Editorial Roles -->
               <author cert="high" key="IA">Ibn al-ʿArabī</author>
               <editor role="role" key="key">Other Roles</editor>
               <persName role="att" key="IA">Ibn al-ʿArabī</persName>
               <note type="authentificationType" subtype="C">Copy</note>
               <note type="authenticityNote">Note on Authenticity</note>
               <!-- Composition History -->
               <date type="fmDate" calendar="Hijri-qamari">611H</date>
               <date type="fmEarliestMS" calendar="Hijri-qamari">640</date>
               <date when="1111" cert="high" calendar="Hijri-qamari">Date of Composition</date>
               <date from="1111" to="1111" cert="medium" calendar="Hijri-qamari">Period of Composition</date>
               <date notBefore="1111"
                     notAfter="1111"
                     cert="low"
                     calendar="Hijri-qamari"
                     evidence="conjecture">Terminus post quem and terminus ante quem</date>
               <note type="dateNote">Note on Date of Composition</note>
               <placeName type="fmPlace">Aleppo</placeName>
               <note type="placeNote">Note on Place of Composition</note>
               <note type="compositionNote"/>
               <!-- Contents -->
               <noteGrp type="workDesc">
                  <note type="description">Commentary by IA himself on his cycle of love poetry, Tarjumān al-Ashwāq (RG 767), bringing out the esoteric meaning of the verses. As IA explains in the preface, he wrote it at the request of Badr al-Ḥabashī and Ibn Sawdakīn in Aleppo in 611H because it had incited the disapproval of some of the local ʿulamāʾ.</note>
                  <note type="structure">Structure of Work</note>
                  <note type="contentsNote">Note on Contents</note>
               </noteGrp>
               <!-- Stemmatics -->
               <note type="stemmatics">A much copied work, verified by two historic mss., Evkaf Muzesi 1713 (873H) and Fatih 5322 (934H), which are both copied from originals written by Ayyūb b. Badr, with samāʿ dated 626H and 616H resp. Most mss. also include the full text of the Tarjuman (RG 767), of which there are also some separate copies. Copy in Baghdad, Iraq Museum 11086/2 which a cataloguer believed was copied in the 7th century (al-Furqān online: https://www.al-furqan.com/our_is_item/manid/1250158/groupid/139348) See: مخطوطات الأدب في المتحف العراقي = Makhṭūṭāt al-adab fī al-Matḥaf al-ʿIrāqī = Catalogue of Manuscripts of Literature In the Iraq Museum Library, p.444 (#1155). After transcribing the usual text in which IA gives the reason he wrote the work the catalogue has this: فرغ منه المؤلف سنة 614H بمدرسة الامير مظفر الدين محمود This information does not occur in most mss: completed 614H in the madrasah of Amīr Muẓaffar al-dīn Maḥmūd. (It occurs in the Shuqayrī edition of 1995).</note>
