                     notAfter="1111"
                     cert="low"
                     calendar="Hijri-qamari"
                     evidence="conjecture">Terminus post quem and terminus ante quem</date>
               <note type="dateNote">Note on Date of Composition</note>
               <placeName type="fmPlace">Damascus</placeName>
               <note type="placeNote">Note on Place of Composition</note>
               <note type="compositionNote"/>
               <!-- Contents -->
               <noteGrp type="workDesc">
                  <note type="description">Commentaries on the 99 Divine Names of God. After a brief introduction in which the traditional theological categories of the Names are laid out, the 99 Names of God (as in al-Ghazālī’s listing) are treated according to three concepts (first proposed by Abū Madyan): taʿalluq (dependence); taḥaqquq (realisation); and takhalluq (assimilation). Critical edition and Spanish translation by P. Beneito.</note>
                  <note type="structure">Structure of Work</note>
                  <note type="contentsNote">Note on Contents</note>
               </noteGrp>
               <!-- Stemmatics -->
               <note type="stemmatics">OY lists 22 mss., although none can be considered truly historic. However, the evidence is compelling: Ulu Cami 1581 (c.826H) may have been copied from an original, as it carries a note by IA about the composition of the work, that it was written in Ramaḍān 621H for a known disciple, Sharafuddīn Abū Muḥammad ʿAbd al-Wāḥid b. Abū Bakr b. Sulaymān al-Ḥamawī. The earliest copy is Fatih 5298, dated 783H, which also has a colophon saying that it is a work by IA and that it was dictated to a student in 621H in Damascus. A work of this title is listed in both the lists which IA made of his own works, Fihris muʾallafāt al-shaykh al-akbar (RG142) and Ijāza l-il-malik al-Muẓaffar (RG 269), and there is a correspondence with other works on the Divine Names (see FM 559).</note>
               <!-- Related Works -->
               <relatedItem type="type" target="#work_id"/>
               <note type="relationsNote">Note on Related Works</note>
               <!-- References to This Work in Other Works -->
               <noteGrp type="references2ThisWork">
                  <note type="ijazaBadawi" resp="Badawī" n="17">17</note>
                  <note type="fihrisAwwad" resp="Awwād" n="17">17</note>
                  <note type="futuhatOY" resp="OY"/>
                  <note type="other"/>
                  <note target="#ijaza">Reference to work in the Ijāza</note>
