               <note type="authenticityNote">Note on Authenticity</note>
               <!-- Composition History -->
               <date type="fmDate" calendar="Hijri-qamari">595</date>
               <date type="fmEarliestMS" calendar="Hijri-qamari">&lt;638</date>
               <date when="1111" cert="high" calendar="Hijri-qamari">Date of Composition</date>
               <date from="1111" to="1111" cert="medium" calendar="Hijri-qamari">Period of Composition</date>
               <date notBefore="1111"
                     notAfter="1111"
                     cert="low"
                     calendar="Hijri-qamari"
                     evidence="conjecture">Terminus post quem and terminus ante quem</date>
               <note type="dateNote">Note on Date of Composition</note>
               <placeName type="fmPlace">Alméria</placeName>
               <note type="placeNote">Note on Place of Composition</note>
               <note type="compositionNote">According to Fut I. 347, this work was written in 595H, in 11 days during the month of Ramadan. It is dedicated to al-Habashi.</note>
               <!-- Contents -->
               <noteGrp type="workDesc">
                  <note type="description">Written for IA’s close companion, Badr al-Ḥabashī, this is said to be the book that explains what all spiritual masters need to teach. It describes three degrees of surrender (islām), faith (īmān) and true goodness (iḥsān), according to three levels of realisation. It includes a detailed discussion of how all the members and faculties of the human being participate in the Divine Praise.</note>
                  <note type="structure">Structure of Work</note>
                  <note type="contentsNote">Note on Contents</note>
               </noteGrp>
               <!-- Stemmatics -->
               <note type="stemmatics">A much copied work, verified by at least four historic mss. The best is Yusuf Ağa 5001, written by SQ in the lifetime of IA, with a samāʿ signed by IA, although it is badly water-damaged, and Majles 594 (652H) which is taken from a copy made in Damascus in 606H. Other mss identified by JC: Bayazid 3466 (735H?)</note>
