               <note type="placeNote">Note on Place of Composition</note>
               <note type="compositionNote">29 Jumādā l-ūlā 601H in Mosul (Vel/51/68b)</note>
               <!-- Contents -->
               <noteGrp type="workDesc">
                  <note type="description">Treatise on all the Qur’anic passages relating to the name Rabb (Lord), interpreting them in a mystical manner.</note>
                  <note type="structure">Structure of Work</note>
                  <note type="contentsNote">Note on Contents</note>
               </noteGrp>
               <!-- Stemmatics -->
               <note type="stemmatics">OY lists 17 mss., of which two can be considered historic. The best is Veliyuddin 51 (c.782H, copied from an original in the hand of IA.) According to OY, it was written 601H in Jerusalem on the basis of a note on Veliyuddin 51, but our investigation shows that he has confused the place of copying with the place of writing. In fact, the note says that IA wrote the original ms. in Mosul in 601H. (See Jane Clark and Denis McAuley Some Notes on the Manuscript Veliyuddin 51, JMIAS 40, 2006.)</note>
