                     cert="low"
                     calendar="Hijri-qamari"
                     evidence="conjecture">Terminus post quem and terminus ante quem</date>
               <note type="dateNote">Note on Date of Composition</note>
               <placeName type="fmPlace">Hebron</placeName>
               <note type="placeNote">Note on Place of Composition</note>
               <note type="compositionNote"/>
               <!-- Contents -->
               <noteGrp type="workDesc">
                  <note type="description">On the intuitive knowledge which leads to certitude. Written in Palestine in the Mosque of Yaqīn (see Veliyuddin 1826). Shehit Ali 1341 also has a note about its composition in 602H, stating that it was written in one day on Wednesday 14th Shawwāl 602H on the way to visit the tombs of Lot and Abraham.</note>
                  <note type="structure">Structure of Work</note>
                  <note type="contentsNote">Note on Contents</note>
               </noteGrp>
               <!-- Stemmatics -->
               <note type="stemmatics">OY lists 27 mss., of which at least two can be considered historic. The best is Veliyuddin 1826 (c.825H, copied from an original by Ayyūb b. Badr and read before IA in 621H).</note>
